IRL there were tactical nuclear artillery shells in the 1950s. I don't know what the yields are but even the biggest one there has an area of effect 6km across. That page doesn't seem to talk about conventional vehicles, infantry, fallout, or radiation, but for the kind of surface detonation it describes, human beings in the open get third degree thermal burns out to about double the 5 PSI radius and I will also note that 1 PSI overpressure, which goes further out than that, at least with this range of yields, will do damage to buildings anywhere between shattering all the windows to partially collapsing them, depending on construction. If we use the established terms used in a lot of papers, where "moderate damage" is within the 5 PSI overpressure radius, and "heavy damage" at least 20 PSI overpressure. This is typically about half the distance of 5 PSI overpressure at the surface. The biggest one there seems to be in the 250-300 kiloton range, which is well into the "city buster" class but very far from the biggest ever created. It seems not too different, if I'm reading the Wikipedia articles correctly, from estimates about the old W87 warhead, which, reentry vehicle and all, doesn't seem to be "very large." But maybe in the Battletech 'verse nuclear weapons are gigantic things the size of Fat Man that have to be loaded onto an enormous jet bomber, or maybe there's a giant slingshot. The scatter rules indicate a circular error probable that's comparable to modern SLBMs, if I'm reading it, and the articles, correctly.

tl;dr it's weird, man

Battletech is a strange mistress. It's sorta retro-future. Some planets being essentially isolated from the larger group of humanity. But they do manufacture weapons and new mechs. Some like the Steiners would BURY opponents in heavy assault mechs.

But in the setting the Ares Conventions were signed as gentlemen rules for the ruling families. Nukes were no longer used in warfare, because during the hayday of the age of war, they would essentially carpet bomb planets with nukes. The signing of the convention set the ground rules to keep everyone from wiping everything out in radioactive fire or orbital shelling.

But the story goes on from there, with the succession wars, the reunification war, the clan wars, ad infinitum. Shit changed hand to hand. Terrorists would get their hands on nukes. Assassinations would happen with nukes. The timelines are all well documented.
